abstract: >
  MitoFlow is a Python-based pipeline for detecting and quantifying mitochondrial
  fission and fusion events in 4D confocal microscopy data. Starting from
  binarized mitochondrial masks, MitoFlow performs 3D
  segmentation, multi-criteria tracking, and event calling to build full
  mitochondrial lineages over time. For each timepoint, individual mitochondria
  are labeled in 3D via connected-component analysis (6-connected components, default) and annotated with volume,
  physical centroid coordinates, and sphere radius. Across
  consecutive frames, candidate parentâ€“child links are proposed based on voxel
  overlap and centroid proximity (KD-tree search) and scored with a composite
  cost function that combines overlap (IoU), distance, and relative volume
  change, followed by Hungarian matching to obtain consistent tracks. Fission
  and fusion events are detected from one-to-many and many-to-one transitions
  that satisfy overlap and volume-conservation criteria, and are filtered by a
  persistence requirement (default 1-frame). The pipeline exports a directed lineage graph,
  rich tabular outputs, and voxel-wise label/track volumes, and provides
  Napari and HTML-report interfaces for interactive quality control and
  figure-ready visualizations.

